<dl id="n36190e"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n36" href="#n36190e">N36 (VI.B.29)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n36all.htm#n36190e"> 190(e)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> peltries <small>Orange</small></blockquote> <dd class="well"> <ul class="list-inline" id="n36190e"><li>FW 548.26 </li><li><a href="../../flex/rB/lexrB.htm#n36190e">2010</a> </li><li><a href="../../flex/rB/l39rB.htm#n36190e">1939</a> </li><li><ms href="#n36190e">MS BL 47484b-449</ms> </li><li>JJA 59:191 <a name="rBd14" href="../../ff/fdra/rda.htm#rBd14">Usage</a> </li><li> <a href="../../flex/rB/rBd14.htm#n36190e">Draft: III&sect;3B.14</a></li> </ul> <blockquote class="sources">A mutual good-will, however, existed between <font color="green">[the Indians]</font> and the burghers of New Amsterdam. Our benevolent forefathers endeavoured as much as possible to ameliorate their situation by giving them gin, rum, and glass beads in return for their <mark>peltries</mark> <font color="green">[pelts or skins]</font>, for it seems the kind-hearted Dutchmen had conceived a great friendship for the savage neighbors, on account of their being pleasant men to trade with, and little skilled in the art of making a bargain. <font color="green">[KNY 220: The Van Pelts were mighty hunters of minks and musk-rats, whence came the word Peltry]</font> <small> Washington Irving, <a name="WINY" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#WINY"><cite title="source">A History of New York, by Diedrich Knickerbocker</cite></a> (ed. unknown) 68ff</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
